[[Image:Kodaikanal Solar Observatory-b.jpg|thumb|Solar Tunnel Telescope at Kodaikanal]] '''Amil Kumar Das''' (1902&nbsp;– February 18, 1961) was an [[India]]n [[astronomer]]. During the [[International Geophysical Year]], observatories in [[Madrid]], [[India]], and [[Manila]] were responsible for monitoring solar effects. The [[Kodaikanal Solar Observatory]] in [[South India]] performed this monitoring using their recently built [[Kodaikanal Solar Observatory#Solar Tunnel Telescope|solar tunnel telescope]]. Dr. Das was the director of the Kodaikanal observatory at this time. In 1960 he was responsible for installing a tower/tunnel telescope at the facility that would be used to perform some of the first ever helioseismology investigations.<ref name="bappu">{{cite journal|last=Bappu|first=M.K.V.|date=June 2000|title=The Kodaikanal Observatory - A Historical Account |journal= Journal of Astrophysics and Astronomy|publisher=Indian Academy of Sciences|location=Bangalore|volume=21|pages=105|url=http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu//full/seri/JApA./0021//0000105.000.html|doi=10.1007/bf02702374|bibcode=2000JApA...21..103.}}</ref> The crater [[Das (crater)|Das]] on the [[Far side (Moon)|far side]] of the [[Moon]] is named after him.
==External links== * [https://web.archive.org/web/20051120040908/http://www.vigyanprasar.com/dream/dec99/article1.htm Indian Astronomy : From Jantar-Mantar to Kavalur]
