{{more footnotes|date=March 2013}} {{Infobox scientist |name = Aristid Lindenmayer |image = <!--(filename only)--> |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1925|11|17}} |birth_place = [[Budapest]] |death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1989|10|30|1925|11|17}} |death_place = |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = Hungarian |ethnicity = |fields = |workplaces = |alma_mater = [[Eötvös Loránd University|University of Budapest]] |doctoral_advisor = |academic_advisors = |doctoral_students = |notable_students = |known_for = [[L-system]]s |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |awards = |religion = |signature = <!--(filename only)--> |footnotes = }}
'''Aristid Lindenmayer''' (17 November 1925 – 30 October 1989) was a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[biologist]]. In 1968 he developed a type of [[formal languages]] that is today called [[L-system]]s or Lindenmayer Systems. Using those systems Lindenmayer modelled the behaviour of cells of plants. L-systems nowadays are also used to model whole plants.
[[Image:Fractal weeds.jpg|thumb|300px|Plant generated using an L-system in 3D.]] Lindenmayer worked with [[yeast]] and filamentous [[fungi]] and studied the growth patterns of various types of algae, such as the blue/green bacteria [[Anabaena|''Anabaena catenula'']]. Originally the L-systems were devised to provide a formal description of the development of such simple multicellular organisms, and to illustrate the neighbourhood relationships between plant cells. Later on, this system was extended to describe higher plants and complex branching structures.
==Career== Lindenmayer studied chemistry and biology at the [[Eötvös Loránd University|University of Budapest]] from 1943 to 1948. He received his Ph.D. in plant physiology in 1956 at the [[University of Michigan]].<ref name="Franklin1974">{{cite book|author=James Franklin|title=The Rhode Island Almanack|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7TIIAAAAIAAJ|year=1974|publisher=John Carter Brown Library|page=190}}</ref> In 1968 he became professor in Philosophy of Life Sciences and Biology at the [[Utrecht University|University of Utrecht]], The Netherlands. From 1972 onward he headed the Theoretical Biology Group at Utrecht University.<ref>Przemyslaw Prusinkiewicz, Martin de Boer (1991) Obituary Aristid Lindenmayer (1925-1989), ''Int. J. General Systems'', Vol 18, pp. 289-290 1991</ref>
==Publications== *Aristid Lindenmayer, "Mathematical models for cellular interaction in development." ''J. Theoret. Biology,'' 18:280—315, 1968. *{{cite book|first=Przemysław|last=Prusinkiewicz|authorlink=Przemysław Prusinkiewicz|author2=Aristid Lindenmayer |title=The Algorithmic Beauty of Plants (The Virtual Laboratory)|publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer-Verlag]]|year=1990|isbn=0-387-97297-8|url=http://algorithmicbotany.org/papers/#abop}} (available as a [[PDF]]) *[http://www.informatik.uni-trier.de/~ley/db/indices/a-tree/l/Lindenmayer:Aristid.html Further publications]
