{{more citations needed|date=February 2016}}
The '''Jones-Dole equation''' or Jones-Dole expression is an empirical expression that describes the relationship between the [[viscosity]] of a [[solution]] and the concentration of solute within the solution (at a fixed temperature and pressure).<ref>http://www.le.ac.uk/chemistry/thermodynamics/pdfs/3000/Topic2930.pdf</ref> The Jones-Dole equation is written as:<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jones|first=Grinnell|last2=Dole|first2=Malcolm|date=1929-10-01|title=THE VISCOSITY OF AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS OF STRONG ELECTROLYTES WITH SPECIAL REFERENCE TO BARIUM CHLORIDE|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/ja01385a012|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|volume=51|issue=10|pages=2950–2964|doi=10.1021/ja01385a012|issn=0002-7863}}</ref><math display="block">\frac{\eta}{\eta_0} = 1 + A C^\frac{1}{2}+ B C</math>where *''η'' is the viscosity of the solution (at a fixed temperature and pressure) *''η<sub>0</sub>'' is the viscosity of the solvent at the same temperature and pressure *''A'' is a [[coefficient]] that describes the impact of charge-charge interactions on the viscosity of a solution (it is usually positive) and can be calculated from [[Debye–Hückel theory|Debye-Hückel]] theory. *''B'' is a coefficient that characterises the solute-solvent interactions at a defined temperature and pressure. *''C'' is the solute concentration
The Jones-Dole ''B'' coefficient<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jenkins|first=H. Donald B.|last2=Marcus|first2=Yizhak.|date=1995-12-01|title=Viscosity B-Coefficients of Ions in Solution|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/cr00040a004|journal=Chemical Reviews|volume=95|issue=8|pages=2695–2724|doi=10.1021/cr00040a004|issn=0009-2665}}</ref> is often used to classify ions as either structure makers (kosmotropes) or structure breakers (chaotropes) according to their supposed strengthening or weakening of the hydrogen-bond network of water.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marcus|first=Yizhak|date=2009-03-11|title=Effect of Ions on the Structure of Water: Structure Making and Breaking|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/cr8003828|journal=Chemical Reviews|volume=109|issue=3|pages=1346–1370|doi=10.1021/cr8003828|issn=0009-2665}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ball|first=Philip|last2=Hallsworth|first2=John E.|date=2015-03-23|title=Water structure and chaotropicity: their uses, abuses and biological implications|url=http://xlink.rsc.org/?DOI=C4CP04564E|journal=Physical Chemistry Chemical Physics|language=en|volume=17|issue=13|pages=8297–8305|doi=10.1039/c4cp04564e|issn=1463-9084}}</ref> The Jones-Dole expression works well up to about 1 M but at higher concentrations breaks down as the viscosity of all solutions increase rapidly at high concentrations.
The large increase in viscosity as a function of solute concentration seen in all solutions above about 1 M is the effect of a [[Jamming (physics)|jamming]] transition at a high concentration. As a result, the viscosity increases exponentially as a function of concentration and diverges at a critical concentration. This has been referred to as the Mayonnaise Effect<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wynne|first=Klaas|date=2017-12-08|title=The Mayonnaise Effect|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.jpclett.7b03207|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters|pages=6189–6192|doi=10.1021/acs.jpclett.7b03207|issn=1948-7185}}</ref> as the viscosity of [[mayonnaise]] (essentially a solution of oil in water) is extremely high because of the jamming of micrometer scale droplets.
